</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,151,605]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
DISTRIBUTION. West from 
<collectingCountry box="[466,533,152,176]" name="Egypt" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Egypt</collectingCountry>
along the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden, Arabian Peninsula, 
<collectingCountry box="[1279,1327,152,175]" name="Iraq" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Iraq</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1342,1404,151,176]" name="Syria" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Syria</collectingCountry>
, S 
<collectingCountry box="[151,235,187,212]" name="Turkey" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Turkey</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[246,294,188,211]" name="Iran" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Iran</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[305,445,187,212]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[456,554,187,212]" name="Pakistan" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
, NW 
<collectingCountry box="[618,679,187,212]" name="India" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,151,605]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
DISTRIBUTION IN 
<collectingCountry box="[348,405,224,247]" name="Iran" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">IRAN</collectingCountry>
. 
<figureCitation box="[419,501,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 38–43. 38" captionStartId="78.[151,264,1557,1580]" captionTargetBox="[171,1416,213,1516]" captionTargetId="figure-53@78.[151,1436,193,1536]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 38–43. 38. Cyrtopodion kachhense. 39. Cyrtopodion kiabii. 40. Cyrtopodion kirmanense. 41. Cyrtopodion persepolense. 42. Cyrtopodion scabrum. 43. Cyrtopodion sistanense." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4929726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4929726/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
. Most of Iran including the Mesopotamian Plain in the west through the Zagros and the central Plateau continuously to Afghanistan and Pakistan in the east. A recent record from the logistically important city of Rasht, 
<collectingRegion box="[443,578,294,319]" country="Iran" name="Gilan" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Gilan Prov.</collectingRegion>
could be explained as a range expansion facilitated by human mediated dispersal (
<bibRefCitation author="Rastegar-Pouyani, N. &amp; Khosravani, A. &amp; Oraie, H." box="[265,609,330,355]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="61 - 63" refId="ref63538" refString="Rastegar-Pouyani, N., Khosravani, A. &amp; Oraie, H. (2010 a) A new record of Cyrtopodion scabrum (Heyden, 1827) from the Caspian Sea Coastal Region, Guilan Province, Northern Iran. Herpetology Notes, 3, 61 - 63." type="journal article" year="2010">
Rastegar-Pouyani 
<emphasis box="[473,529,330,355]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2010a
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,151,605]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
HABITAT. A typical synanthropic gecko with strong affinity to human habitations. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1167,1212,367,390]" name="Iran" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Iran</collectingCountry>
found on walls of inhabited and abandoned buildings, brick fences, garden walls or in dumping grounds; also dry scrubland and stony hillsides where it seeks refuge in crevices and fissures (
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, S. C." box="[770,948,437,462]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref45318" refString="Anderson, S. C. (1999) The lizards of Iran. Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles, Oxford, Ohio, 442 pp." type="book" year="1999">Anderson 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Khan, M. S." box="[959,1087,437,462]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref56151" refString="Khan, M. S. (2006) Amphibians and Reptiles of Pakistan. Krieger Publishing Company, Malabar, Florida, 311 pp." type="book" year="2006">Khan 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
